text.Taxonomy and naming:
Boronia juncea was first formally described in 1845 by Friedrich Gottlieb Bartling and the description was published in Plantae Preissianae. The specific epithet (juncea) is a Latin word meaning "of rushes".There are four subspecies intergrading with each other:

Boronia juncea subsp. juncea has hairless pedicels and sepals;
Boronia juncea subsp. laniflora has woolly sepals and petals, the sepals 1.5–3 mm (0.059–0.12 in) long;
Boronia juncea subsp. micrantha has woolly sepals and petals, the sepals 3–5 mm (0.12–0.20 in) long with a sharply pointed tip;
Boronia juncea subsp. minima has woolly sepals and petals, the sepals 3–5 mm (0.12–0.20 in) long with a tapered tip.
